    "title": "5 Small Business Marketing Hacks That Donâ€™t Require Selling a Kidney",
    "slug": "5-small-business-marketing-hacks-that-dont-require-selling-a-kidney",
    "content": "<p>Small business marketing doesnâ€™t have to feel like driving a 1989 sedan with three missing hubcaps and an â€œI brake for squirrelsâ€ bumper sticker. You donâ€™t need a Madison Avenue budget or a secret marketing degree to make big improvements. You just need a few quick fixes, and maybe a sense of humor when things get weird.</p><p>Here are five quick ways to tune up your small business marketing without selling a kidney:</p><ol><li><strong>Stop Whispering Into the Void (a.k.a. Claim Your Google Business Profile) â€”</strong>&nbsp;Imagine setting up a shop but forgetting to unlock the front door. Thatâ€™s what itâ€™s like when you donâ€™t claim your Google Business Profile. Itâ€™s free, itâ€™s easy, and itâ€™s the first place customers look for directions, reviews, and your hours.&nbsp;<strong>Pro tip:</strong>&nbsp;Post updates and photos regularly. Bonus if you upload a picture of your staff not looking like theyâ€™ve been kidnapped.</li><li><strong>Write Like a Human, Not a Robot â€”</strong>&nbsp;Weâ€™ve all seen the website copy that reads like a toaster wrote it: â€œWe synergistically leverage innovative solutions to maximize customer-centric paradigms.â€ Please donâ€™t. Instead, write like youâ€™re explaining what you do to your neighbor. Real words, real benefits. Customers donâ€™t care about â€œsolutions.â€ They care that youâ€™ll fix their leaky sink, groom their hairy dog, or make their latte without spelling their name as â€œKhrysthophyr.â€</li><li><strong>Make Social Media a Party, Not a Sales Pitch â€”</strong>&nbsp;Posting â€œBuy now!â€ 37 times a week is like being the guy at the barbecue who only talks about his timeshare. Mix it up.When in doubt, add a dog picture. Science says engagement goes up 472% (okay, maybe not science, but definitely Instagram).<ul><li>Share behind-the-scenes stories.</li><li>Post customer wins.</li><li>Drop a quick tip that makes your followers feel smarter.</li></ul></li><li><strong>Email Is Still Alive (Stop Acting Like Itâ€™s a Fossil) â€”</strong>&nbsp;Yes, people still check their email, usually while pretending to work. Build a simple list of your customers and send a monthly update. It doesnâ€™t have to be fancy.Keep it short. Nobody wants to read your version of&nbsp;<em>War and Peace</em>.<ul><li>Share a tip.</li><li>Highlight a service.</li><li>Remind them you exist.</li></ul></li><li><strong>Track Something (Anything, Please) â€”</strong>&nbsp;Small business marketing isnâ€™t magic. Itâ€™s math in disguise. If youâ€™re spending money on ads, track clicks. If youâ€™re posting on social, track engagement. If youâ€™re sending emails, track opens. Even better: pick one number that matters most (calls, leads, appointments) and focus on making that number go up. Otherwise, youâ€™ll end up like a driver who insists theyâ€™re â€œmaking good timeâ€ while headed the wrong direction.</li></ol><p><strong>Final Lap â€”</strong>&nbsp;Small business marketing doesnâ€™t have to be overwhelming. Start with these quick wins: claim your Google profile, write like a human, mix up your social posts, send short emails, and track at least one thing. Do these consistently and youâ€™ll look less like a marketing rookie and more like someone cruising confidently in the carpool lane.</p><p>Need more help? Thatâ€™s what we do at Marketing Car. We keep your marketing engine humming so you can keep your business moving.</p>",
